<section class="section--tight"><div class="wrap">
  <p class="center muted" style="font-size:.85rem;letter-spacing:.08em;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:22px">One viewer for every large data format</p>
  <div class="formatstrip">
    <span class="fmt">JSON</span><span class="fmt">JSON-Lines / NDJSON</span><span class="fmt">XML</span><span class="fmt">CSV</span><span class="fmt">TSV</span><span class="fmt">Log files</span>
  </div>
</div></section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="how-it-works"><div class="wrap">
  <div class="center"><span class="eyebrow">How it works</span><h2>Open it. Navigate it. Find anything.</h2>
  <p class="lead">Every file is memory-mapped and parsed once into a compact index &mdash; only the rows on screen are ever built.</p></div>
  <div class="steps">
    <div class="step"><div class="step__n">1</div><h3>Open the file</h3><p>Drag in a JSON, NDJSON, XML, CSV or TSV file up to ~10 GB &mdash; or paste from the clipboard or fetch a URL with auth. It opens instantly, no progress bars.</p></div>
    <div class="step"><div class="step__n">2</div><h3>Navigate the tree</h3><p>Everything renders as one uniform, virtualized tree. Jump to any path, bookmark nodes, and read collapsed counts like &ldquo;products : […], 31 items&rdquo;.</p></div>
    <div class="step"><div class="step__n">3</div><h3>Search &amp; export</h3><p>Regex find, live filter, or JSONPath / XPath queries backed by parallel native search. Then export or convert to JSON, XML or CSV.</p></div>
  </div>
</div></section>

<section class="section"><div class="wrap">
  <div class="center"><span class="eyebrow">A whole new class of performance</span><h2>Built for scale, byte by byte.</h2>
  <p class="lead">A native engine treats your data as structure, not text &mdash; so memory tracks your working set, not the file size.</p></div>
  <div class="stats">
    <div class="stat"><div class="stat__num">~10 GB</div><div class="stat__label">Files open &amp; search, no in-memory copy</div></div>
    <div class="stat"><div class="stat__num">24 B</div><div class="stat__label">Index per node &mdash; ~3 GB for 130M nodes</div></div>
    <div class="stat"><div class="stat__num">130M/s</div><div class="stat__label">Objects parsed per second</div></div>
    <div class="stat"><div class="stat__num">2 GB/s</div><div class="stat__label">Raw file read throughput</div></div>
  </div>
</div></section>

<section class="section section--alt"><div class="wrap" style="max-width:920px">
  <div class="center"><span class="eyebrow">163&times; faster load</span><h2>The result speaks for itself.</h2>
  <p class="lead">Approximate load time for a large JSON file. Where general-purpose editors stall or run out of memory, the structural index just opens.</p></div>
  <div class="bench" data-bench>
    <div class="bench__row"><div class="bench__name win">OPENXMLJSON</div><div class="bench__track"><div class="bench__fill win" data-bar="4" style="width:0"></div></div><div class="bench__val">0.4s</div></div>
    <div class="bench__row"><div class="bench__name">Notepad++</div><div class="bench__track"><div class="bench__fill" data-bar="62" style="width:0"></div></div><div class="bench__val">65s</div></div>
    <div class="bench__row"><div class="bench__name">VS Code</div><div class="bench__track"><div class="bench__fill" data-bar="78" style="width:0"></div></div><div class="bench__val">82s</div></div>
    <div class="bench__row"><div class="bench__name">Sublime</div><div class="bench__track"><div class="bench__fill" data-bar="55" style="width:0"></div></div><div class="bench__val">58s</div></div>
    <div class="bench__row"><div class="bench__name">Chrome</div><div class="bench__track"><div class="bench__fill" data-bar="100" style="width:0"></div></div><div class="bench__val">fails</div></div>
  </div>
  <p class="muted center" style="font-size:.8rem;margin-top:26px">Illustrative comparison on a large JSON file. Actual results vary by hardware, file shape and configuration.</p>
</div></section>

<section class="section" id="features"><div class="wrap">
  <div class="center"><span class="eyebrow">Everything you need</span><h2>A data workbench, not a text editor.</h2>
  <p class="lead">Browse and query your files like a database &mdash; with the tools you'd expect from an enterprise DBMS.</p></div>
  <div class="features">
    <div class="feature"><div class="feature__ic"><svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8"><path d="M4 6h16M4 12h16M4 18h10"/></svg></div><h3>Virtualized tree view</h3><p>Objects, arrays, XML elements and CSV records render in one uniform, collapsible tree. Cost per frame tracks visible rows (~40), never file size.</p></div>
    <div class="feature"><div class="feature__ic"><svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8"><path d="M4 6h16M4 12h16M4 18h10"/></svg></div><h3>Regex find, instantly</h3><p>Literal or regex search scoped to keys, values or attributes &mdash; chip-highlighted matches with &#9650;&#9660; stepping, backed by parallel native search.</p></div>
    <div class="feature"><div class="feature__ic"><svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8"><path d="M4 6h16M4 12h16M4 18h10"/></svg></div><h3>JSONPath &amp; XPath queries</h3><p>Query JSON/CSV with $.store.items[*].name and XML with //item/@id. Combine paths to pull several fields at once; results filter the tree.</p></div>
    <div class="feature"><div class="feature__ic"><svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8"><path d="M4 6h16M4 12h16M4 18h10"/></svg></div><h3>On-demand (lazy) indexing</h3><p>Files too large to index eagerly open anyway &mdash; only the paths you expand are materialized, so resident memory tracks the subtree you view.</p></div>
    <div class="feature"><div class="feature__ic"><svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8"><path d="M4 6h16M4 12h16M4 18h10"/></svg></div><h3>CSV spreadsheet view</h3><p>CSV/TSV opens in a grid with header detection. Leading-zero cells like ZIP codes deliberately stay strings &mdash; no silent data loss.</p></div>
    <div class="feature"><div class="feature__ic"><svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8"><path d="M4 6h16M4 12h16M4 18h10"/></svg></div><h3>Follow tail (tail -f)</h3><p>Follow a growing JSON / NDJSON / log file. Only newly appended lines are parsed each tick, so it stays cheap on huge, live files.</p></div>
    <div class="feature"><div class="feature__ic"><svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8"><path d="M4 6h16M4 12h16M4 18h10"/></svg></div><h3>Convert &amp; export</h3><p>Export the whole document or any node as pretty JSON, XML or CSV &mdash; cross-format conversion built in, plus export of search matches.</p></div>
    <div class="feature"><div class="feature__ic"><svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8"><path d="M4 6h16M4 12h16M4 18h10"/></svg></div><h3>Open from URL</h3><p>Fetch a document over HTTP(S) with None / Basic / Bearer / API-Key auth, remember credentials, and copy the request as cURL.</p></div>
    <div class="feature"><div class="feature__ic"><svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8"><path d="M4 6h16M4 12h16M4 18h10"/></svg></div><h3>Node statistics</h3><p>Right-click any container for child counts, a type histogram, distinct values and numeric min / max / avg &mdash; understand your data fast.</p></div>
  </div>
</div></section>

